<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ900824-0046</DOCNO><DOCID>900824-0046.</DOCID><HL>   Business Brief -- Justin Industries Inc.:   Holder Group Seeks Vote   On Planned Lama Purchase</HL><DATE>08/24/90</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION</SO><CO>   JSTN TLAM</CO><IN>TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)</IN><LP>   A group of disgruntled investors asked Justin IndustriesInc. to put to a shareholder vote the company's proposedacquisition of Tony Lama Co.   In a letter to the Justin board, Perry H. Sutherland ofKansas City, Mo., and Barry S. Rosenstein of New York,leaders of a group that owns about 11.8% of Justin, calledthe proposed transaction &quot;astonishing&quot; and said they would&quot;review all of our options to protect our 1,000,000-plusshare investment in the company and that of our fellowshareholders.&quot; An offer by the group to purchase the sharesof Justin it didn't already own was rejected this year by theJustin board.</LP><TEXT>   In Dallas, Justin declined to comment on the request for avote.   Justin has agreed to acquire Tony Lama, based in El Paso,Texas, for $9 a share, or about $18 million, plus theassumption of about $34 million in debt. In the first half of1990, Tony Lama had a loss of $901,000, or 47 cents a share,after a loss of $1.8 million, or 95 cents a share, in 1989.Both companies make Western boots; Justin also makes buildingsupplies and industrial equipment.</TEXT></DOC>